{"title_page": "Priyanka Purohit", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian television actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Priyanka Purohit\n| birth_name         = Priyanka Purohit\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1991|10|07}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai, Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| residence          = [[Mumbai]], [[India]]\n| nationality        = [[India]]n\n| occupation         = [[Actress]]\n| yearsactive        = 2014\u2014present\n| known_for          = ''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]''<br>''[[Krishnadasi]]''\n<br>''[[Tera Kya Hoga Alia]]''}}\n\n'''Priyanka Purohit''' is an Indian television actress known for participating in [[MTV (India)|MTV India]]'s ''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]'' and portraying Poorva Deshmukh in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]''.\n\n==Career==\nPurohit started off her career in 2014 by participating in [[MTV India]]'s ''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]''. In the same year, she made her acting debut as Gauri in [[Sony Pal]]'s ''[[Yeh Dil Sun Raha Hai]].''\n\nIn 2015, she played Pinky in [[Zee TV]]'s ''[[Bandhan (Indian TV series)|Bandhan]]'' and Pallavi in [[Life OK]]'s ''[[Kalash - Ek Vishwaas|Kalash]]''. In 2016, Purohit portrayed Poorva Deshmukh in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]'' opposite [[Shravan Reddy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/priyanka-purohit-romance-shravan-krishndasi-160502|title=Priyanka Purohit to romance Shravan in Krishndasi|last=|first=|date=|work=Tellychakkar|access-date=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, she joined [[Zee TV]]'s ''[[Sanyukt]]'' as Hetal Shah opposite Suraj Kakkar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/priyanka-purohit-and-simran-khanna-zee-tv-s-sanyukt-170104|title=Priyanka Purohit in Zee TV\u2019s Sanyukt|last=|first=|date=|work=Tellychakkar|access-date=|language=en}}</ref> From 2017 to 2018, she portrayed Chandni Kanojia in [[&TV]]'s ''[[Half Marriage (TV series)|Half Marriage]]'' opposite Tarun Mahilani.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/tv/news/hindi/ready-to-witness-a-half-marriage-on-tv/articleshow/60816646.cms|title=Ready to witness a \u2018Half Marriage\u2019 on TV?|last=|first=|date=|work=The Times of India|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2018 to 2019, Purohit portrayed Bhumi in [[Zee TV]]'s ''[[Aap Ke Aa Jane Se]]'' .<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iwmbuzz.com/television/news/priyanka-purohit-enter-zee-tvs-aap-ke-aa-jane-se/2018/07/16|title=Priyanka Purohit to enter Zee TV\u2019s Aap Ke Aa Jane Se|work=IWMBuzz|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2019, she played Tara in [[SAB TV]]'s ''Tera Kya Hoga Alia'' opposite [[Harshad Arora]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iwmbuzz.com/television/news/priyanka-purohit-opposite-harshad-arora-optimystix-show-sab-tv/2019/07/08|title=Priyanka Purohit opposite Harshad Arora in Optimystix show on SAB TV|website=IWM Buzz|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Personal Life==\nPriyanka Purohit has two siblings one younger brother and one elder sister. She dated her fellow Splitsvillain contestant Ayaz Ahmed. She loves singing,dancing and travelling. Her zodiac sign is libra and she is a Hindu. <ref> Priyanka Purohit age,boyfriend,family, biography & more>>StarsUnfolded</ref>\n\n==Television==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! Channel\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]''\n|Contestant\n|[[MTV India]]\n|-\n|2015\u20132015\n|''[[Yeh Dil Sun Raha Hai]]\n|Gauri\n|[[Sony Pal]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2015\n|''[[Bandhan (Indian TV series)|Bandhan]]\n|Pinky Patil\n|[[Zee TV]]\n|-\n|''[[Kalash (2015 TV series)|Kalash]]''\n|Pallavi Deol\n|[[Life OK]]\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]''\n|Poorva Deshmukh\n|[[Colors TV]]\n|-\n| 2017\n|''[[Sanyukt]]''\n|Hetal Shah\n|[[Zee TV]]\n|-\n|2017\u20132018\n|''[[Half Marriage (TV series)|Half Marriage]]''\n|Chandni Kanojia\n|[[&TV]]\n|-\n| 2018\u20132019\n|''[[Aap Ke Aa Jane Se]]''\n|Bhumi\n|[[Zee TV]]\n|-\n|2019\n|''Tera Kya Hoga Alia''\n|Tara\n|[[SAB TV]]\n|}\n\n==Web==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Platform\n|-\n|2020\n|''Sumer Singh Diaries''\n|TBA\n|[[Viu (streaming media)|Viu]]\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Show !! Result !! Reference\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Zee Rishtey Awards]]\n|Favourite Naya Sadasya (Female)\n|''[[Aap Ke Aa Jane Se]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizasialive.com/zee-rishtey-awards-2018-nominations/|title=Zee Rishtey Awards 2018: Nominations|last=|first=|date=|work=Biz Asia|access-date=|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Purohit, Priyanka}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|8636752}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian television actress}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Priyanka Purohit\n| birth_name         = Priyanka Purohit\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1991|10|07}}\n| birth_place        = [[Mumbai, Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n| residence          = [[Mumbai]], [[India]]\n| nationality        = [[India]]n\n| occupation         = [[Actress]]\n| yearsactive        = 2014\u2014present\n| known_for          = ''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]''<br>''[[Krishnadasi]]''\n}}\n\n'''Priyanka Purohit''' is an Indian television actress known for participating in [[MTV (India)|MTV India]]'s ''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]'' and portraying Poorva Deshmukh in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]''.\n\n==Career==\nPurohit started off her career in 2014 by participating in [[MTV India]]'s ''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]''. In the same year, she made her acting debut as Gauri in [[Sony Pal]]'s ''[[Yeh Dil Sun Raha Hai]].''\n\nIn 2015, she played Pinky in [[Zee TV]]'s ''[[Bandhan (Indian TV series)|Bandhan]]'' and Pallavi in [[Life OK]]'s ''[[Kalash - Ek Vishwaas|Kalash]]''. In 2016, Purohit portrayed Poorva Deshmukh in [[Colors TV]]'s ''[[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]'' opposite [[Shravan Reddy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/priyanka-purohit-romance-shravan-krishndasi-160502|title=Priyanka Purohit to romance Shravan in Krishndasi|last=|first=|date=|work=Tellychakkar|access-date=|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, she joined [[Zee TV]]'s ''[[Sanyukt]]'' as Hetal Shah opposite Suraj Kakkar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/priyanka-purohit-and-simran-khanna-zee-tv-s-sanyukt-170104|title=Priyanka Purohit in Zee TV\u2019s Sanyukt|last=|first=|date=|work=Tellychakkar|access-date=|language=en}}</ref> From 2017 to 2018, she portrayed Chandni Kanojia in [[&TV]]'s ''[[Half Marriage (TV series)|Half Marriage]]'' opposite Tarun Mahilani.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/tv/news/hindi/ready-to-witness-a-half-marriage-on-tv/articleshow/60816646.cms|title=Ready to witness a \u2018Half Marriage\u2019 on TV?|last=|first=|date=|work=The Times of India|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2018 to 2019, Purohit portrayed Bhumi in [[Zee TV]]'s ''[[Aap Ke Aa Jane Se]]'' .<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.iwmbuzz.com/television/news/priyanka-purohit-enter-zee-tvs-aap-ke-aa-jane-se/2018/07/16|title=Priyanka Purohit to enter Zee TV\u2019s Aap Ke Aa Jane Se|work=IWMBuzz|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2019, she played Tara in [[SAB TV]]'s ''Tera Kya Hoga Alia'' opposite [[Harshad Arora]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iwmbuzz.com/television/news/priyanka-purohit-opposite-harshad-arora-optimystix-show-sab-tv/2019/07/08|title=Priyanka Purohit opposite Harshad Arora in Optimystix show on SAB TV|website=IWM Buzz|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! Channel\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[MTV Splitsvilla|Splitsvilla 7]]''\n|Contestant\n|[[MTV India]]\n|-\n|2015\u20132015\n|''[[Yeh Dil Sun Raha Hai]]\n|Gauri\n|[[Sony Pal]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|2015\n|''[[Bandhan (Indian TV series)|Bandhan]]\n|Pinky Patil\n|[[Zee TV]]\n|-\n|''[[Kalash (2015 TV series)|Kalash]]''\n|Pallavi Deol\n|[[Life OK]]\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[Krishnadasi (2016 TV series)|Krishnadasi]]''\n|Poorva Deshmukh\n|[[Colors TV]]\n|-\n| 2017\n|''[[Sanyukt]]''\n|Hetal Shah\n|[[Zee TV]]\n|-\n|2017\u20132018\n|''[[Half Marriage (TV series)|Half Marriage]]''\n|Chandni Kanojia\n|[[&TV]]\n|-\n| 2018\u20132019\n|''[[Aap Ke Aa Jane Se]]''\n|Bhumi\n|[[Zee TV]]\n|-\n|2019\n|''Tera Kya Hoga Alia''\n|Tara\n|[[SAB TV]]\n|}\n\n==Web==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Platform\n|-\n|2020\n|''Sumer Singh Diaries''\n|TBA\n|[[Viu (streaming media)|Viu]]\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Show !! Result !! Reference\n|-\n|2018\n|[[Zee Rishtey Awards]]\n|Favourite Naya Sadasya (Female)\n|''[[Aap Ke Aa Jane Se]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizasialive.com/zee-rishtey-awards-2018-nominations/|title=Zee Rishtey Awards 2018: Nominations|last=|first=|date=|work=Biz Asia|access-date=|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Purohit, Priyanka}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|8636752}}\n", "name_user": "Tylertoney Dude perfect", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Added a show)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Priyanka_Purohit"}
{"title_page": "Camillo Berneri", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox philosopher\n| name = Camillo Berneri\n| image = Camillo_Berneri.jpg\n| birth_name = Luigi Camillo Berneri \n| birth_date = May 20, 1897\n| birth_place = [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]], [[Lombardy]],<br>{{flag | Italy | 1861}}\n| death_date = May 5, 1937\n| death_place = [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]],<br>{{flag | Spain | 1931}}\n| alma_mater = [[University of Florence]]\n| school_tradition = [[20th-century philosophy]]\n| main_interests = [[Anarchism]], [[Antifascism]]\n}}\n'''Camillo Berneri''' (also known as '''Camillo da Lodi'''; May 28, 1897, [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]] \u2013 May 5, 1937, [[Barcelona]]) was an [[Italy|Italian]] professor of [[philosophy]], [[anarchist]] militant, propagandist and theorist. He was married to [[Giovanna Berneri]], and was father of [[Marie-Louise Berneri]] and [[Giliana Berneri]], all of whom were also anarchists.\n\n== Biography ==\n=== Early years ===\nCamillo Berneri was born in [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]] on May 20, 1897. His father was a local [[Redshirts (Italy)|redshirt]] official from [[Province of Brescia|Brescia]], his mother was a a primary school teacher from [[Emilia (region of Italy)|Emilia]] and his grandfather was a [[Carbonari]] and a follower of [[Giuseppe Mazzini]].<ref name=\"Dictionary\">{{Cite journal|title= Berneri, Camillo Luigi|journal=Biographical Dictionary of European Labor Leaders|volume=1|first=A. Thomas|last=Lane|page=141-142|isbn=0-313-29899-8|year=1995|url=https://books.google.es/books/about/Biographical_Dictionary_of_European_Labo.html?id=VlR8YCE8lkQC&redir_esc=y}}</ref> His childhood was marked by physical suffering. In just a few months, he became [[malnourished]]. In 1904, Camillo fell ill with [[typhoid fever]], and later [[gastroenteritis]]. He moved with his family first to [[Milan]], then to [[Palermo]], to [[Forl\u00ec]], to [[Varallo Sesia]] and, finally, to [[Reggio Emilia]]. Here, in 1912, Berneri became a member of the ''Reggio Emilia Socialist Youth Federation''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://struggle.ws/spain/berneri.html|title=Camillo Berneri \u2013 Biography of the Italian anarchist|author=|website=struggle.ws|date=2011-05-25|publisher=}}</ref> He joined its Central Committee and collaborated with the federation's national organ. But after intense discussions, in particular with [[Torquato Gobbi]], a bookbinder and member of the ''International Committee of Anarchist Actions'', he left the federation in 1915. In an open letter, Bernery criticized the group for its [[red tape]] and \"lack of devotion.\"<ref name=\"Aktion\">Camillo Berneri, ''[https://www.anarchismus.at/anarchistische-klassiker/camillo-berneri/88-camillo-berneri-der-arbeiterkult Der Arbeiterkult]'', 1934 (''[[Die Aktion]]'', Nr. 170/174, July 1997)</ref><ref name=\"Mimmo\">{{cite book |first= Mimmo |last=Franzinelli|title= I tentacoli dell'Ovra. Agenti, collaboratori e vittime della polizia politica fascista |publisher= Bollati Boringhieri |year= 1999}}</ref> In 1916 he moved to [[Arezzo]] where he attended high school.\n\n{{quote|The socialist movement began its catastrophic descent into the foundations of destructive egoism, thereby following the trajectory of the moral strength of Christianity, which became powerful thanks to its martyrs and fell into decline when the sacrifices of its supporters ceased. [...] We need a new upsurge, we need a return to the time when to love the Idea meant not to be afraid of death and not to sacrifice our whole lives for the sake of complete submission. <ref>[[Frank Mintz]], [http://www.fondation-besnard.org/spip.php?article326 ''Camillo Berneri et Francesco Barbieri''].</ref>}}\n\nBerneri joined the [[Anarchism in Italy|Italian anarchist movement]]. He described his departure from [[socialism]] with the words: \u201cThe ideal worker of [[Marxism]] or socialism is a mythical figure. It stems from the metaphysics of socialist romanticism and is not historically proven.\u201d<ref name=\"Aktion\"/> He was struck by the gesture of his comrades, who, despite leaving, wanted him to chair their last meeting in Reggio, and the gesture of his mentor [[Camillo Prampolini]], who called him to find out the reasons for their disagreement. Berneri would always point to \u201cpleasant memories of the socialist period.\u201d<ref name=\"Psychology\">{{cite book|title='' Mussolini-Psychology of a dictator ''|first=Camillo|last=Berneri|publisher=Joint Action Editions|editor=[[Pier Carlo Masini]]|location=Milan|date=1966|page=115\u2014117}}</ref> In 1916, he moved to Arezzo, where he graduated from high school.\n\nOn January 4, 1917, he married in [[Giovanna Berneri|Giovanna Caleffi]], his mother's former pupil. Three months after the wedding, he was called up for military service, however, he was removed from service due to a serious illness. After three years of military service, he was forced to leave the [[Military Academy of Modena]] because of his [[anti-militarist]] activities. Under protection, he was sent to the front and twice brought before a [[military court]]. In 1919 he was confined to the island of [[Pianosa]] because of his participation in a [[Biennio Rosso|general strike on July 20-21, 1919]]. Dismissed from the army in 1919, he began to work diligently with the [[Umanit\u00e0 Nova|anarchist press]] and participated in the creation of the [[Union of Anarchist Communist of Italy|Union of Italian Anarchists]].<ref> '' Camillo Berneri (Lodi 1897-Barcelona 1937) '', Europe of tomorrow, biographical dictionary </ref> Being a convinced anti-militarist, he wrote: \u201cslaughter, robbery, rape, this is war! To satisfy his lust, the vile person takes on the courage that leaves him when he must save his neighbor from danger or start a dangerous and painful business. In a warmed-up and blood-soaked atmosphere of war, an ordinary person falls into barbarism, and sometimes even turns into a beast.\u201d<ref name=\"Aktion\"/> In 1920, he actively participated in the seizure of factories in [[Northern Italy]]. He also made friends with [[Errico Malatesta]] and [[Luigi Fabbri]]. \n\nAfter the war, he graduated from the [[University of Florence]], where Camillo was a student of [[Gaetano Salvemini]]. He then became a professor of philosophy at the university and later went on to teach philosophy at [[University of Camerino|Camerino]].\n\nWhen the [[Italian fascists|fascists]] seized power, Camillo refused to be loyal to the regime. Berneri's aversion to [[fascism]] was ready and decisive, he maintained contact with the [[Florence|Florentine]] [[anti-fascists]]. Berneri's activity in the Union of Italian Anarchists was very intense in those years. When the [[Fascist Italy (1922\u20131943)|fascist dictatorship]] intensified, in May 1926, Berneri was forced to flee the country to [[Third French Republic|France]]. His wife, [[Giovanna Berneri]],<ref> {{Cite web | url = http://www.ephemanar.net/mai04.html#caleffi | title = Giovannina Caleffi | author = | website = [[L'\u00c9ph\u00e9m\u00e9ride Anarchiste]] | date = | publisher =}} </ref> and his daughters [[Marie Louise Berneri]]<ref> {{Cite web | url = http://www.ephemanar.net/avril13.html#bernerimarie|title=Marie Louise Berneri | author = | website = [[L'\u00c9ph\u00e9m\u00e9ride Anarchiste]] | date = | publisher =}} </ref> and [[Giliana Berneri]]<ref> {{Cite web | url = http://www.ephemanar.net/octobre05.html#bernerigiliana | title = Giliana Berneri | author = | website = [[L'\u00c9ph\u00e9m\u00e9ride Anarchiste]] | date = | publisher =}} </ref> joined him soon after.<ref> {{Cite web | url = https://libcom.org/history/berneri-luigi-camillo-1897-1937 | title = Berneri, Luigi Camillo, 1897-1937 | author = | website = Libcom.org | date = 2004-09-21 | publisher =}} </ref>\n\n=== Emigration and police harassment ===\nBerneri was arrested in April 1927, after an international conference in [[L'Ha\u00ff-les-Roses]]. On December 11, 1928, he was expelled from France and until 1930 was constantly harassed by the [[Law enforcement in Belgium|Belgian]], [[Law enforcement in France|French]], [[Law enforcement in the Netherlands|Dutch]], [[Law enforcement in Germany|German]] and [[Grand Ducal Police|Luxembourg]] police during subsequent transfers and spent a lot of time in prison. He received a residence permit in France only in 1935, shortly before leaving for Spain. However, he continued to be widely published in the anarchist press in [[Fascist Italy (1922\u20131943)|Italy]], [[Switzerland]], the [[USA]] and [[Third French Republic|France]]. <ref> {{Cite web | url = http://www.anarca-bolo.ch/cbach/biografie.php? Id = 4 | title = Berneri Camillo Luigi | author = | website = anarca-bolo.ch | date = | publisher =}} </ref>\n\nDespite all his limitations, this period allowed him to read books on various topics such as [[science]], [[psychology]] and [[teleology]]. He wrote [[anti-religious]] articles and brochures as well as pieces on the [[Women's rights|emancipation of women]]. He also completed his dissertation, ''The Anti-Semitic Jew'', where he studied the forced or voluntary [[Jewish assimilation|assimilation of Jews]]. The poet [[Andre Speer]], considered this book \u201cof paramount importance\u201d. Other important writings of his during this time were ''Spying'', ''Fascist Spying Abroad'' and ''Mussolini conquering the Balearic Islands''.\n\nHe also wrote about anarchism, where he defends personal positions:\n\n{{quote|We must move away from romanticism. Look at the masses, I would say, in perspective. There are not homogeneous people, but crowds, diverse, divided into groups. There is no revolutionary will of the masses, but revolutionary moments in which the masses are a huge lever.}}\n\n{{quote|If we want to achieve a significant revision of our revolutionary power, we must get rid of ideological [[a priori]]s and conveniently postponing the solution of tactical and constructive problems for tomorrow. I mean that the biggest danger of stopping and deviating from the revolution lies in the conservative tendency of the masses.}}\n\n=== Spanish Civil War ===\n[[File: Berneri1.jpg | alt = | thumb | Camillo Berneri in 1936]]\nOnce the [[Spanish Civil War]] broke out, Berneri was among the first to rush to [[Revolutionary Catalonia|Catalonia]], the center of a revolution spearheaded by the [[Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional del Trabajo]]: here he found himself alongside [[Carlo Rosselli]] with a large number of [[Anti-fascism#Italy: against Fascism and Mussolini|Italian]] and [[International Brigades|International]] anti-fascists.<ref> {{Cite web | url = https://gimenologues.org/spip.php?Article685 | title = Les Italiens - Charla sur les volontaires internationaux | author = | website = gimenologues.org | date = 2016-10-06 | publisher =}} </ref> Beyond militant solidarity, Carlo Rosselli was tied to his critical support for the prospects of [[Bolshevism]], while in those years Camillo Berneri collaborated with the clandestine organ of the libertarian socialist movement \"Giustizia e Libert\u00e0\", arguing with Rosselli on the stark differences between [[libertarian socialism]] and [[Authoritarian socialism|despotic socialism]]. Together with Rosselli, he organized the first column of Italian volunteers to fight on the [[Aragon front]], which were incorporated into the militia column of [[Joaqu\u00edn Ascaso]]. On August 28, 1936, Camillo Berneri took part in [[Battle of Monte Pelado]] near [[Huesca]]: \u201cWe defended our position with 130 people against 600, hardened and with strong weapons, for four hours of battle.\" He eventually needed to leave the front due to medical problems and returned to Barcelona, \u200b\u200bwhere he created and was editor-in-chief of the newspaper ''Class War'', also collaborating in the CNT-FAI radio station in Barcelona. During his stay in Barcelona, \u200b\u200bBerneri came to be under the surveillance of [[OVRA]], the secret police of fascist Italy.<ref>{{cite book|last=Graham| first=Helen|title=The Spanish Republic at War 1936-1939 | year = 2002 | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]]|page=295}}</ref>\n\nBerneri was a staunch defender of the [[Spanish Revolution of 1936|Spanish Revolution]] and was one of the first to argue that only an [[anti-capitalist]] struggle can counter [[fascism]] and that the problem with [[anti-fascism]] is the rejection of the principles of the [[Social revolution]]. He constantly reiterates that revolution must be won on social, not military, grounds. Thus, he opposed the [[Militarism | militarization]] of the militias, which had brought the first victories against state forces. <ref> {{cite book| title = Guerre de Classes en Espagne et textes libertaires|publisher = [[Spartacus Editions]] | date = 1977}}</ref> He stood against those who advocated the idea of \u200b\u200b\u201cfirst beat [[Francisco Franco|Franco]]\u201d, and stood for the close connection between the war and the social revolution: \u201cVictory in war is necessary; however, the war will not be won by limiting the problem to the purely military conditions of victory, but by linking them to the political and social conditions of victory. '' '<ref>{{Cite news|title = La R\u00e9volution et la Guerre d\u2019Espagne | last=Brou\u00e9|first=P.| url = https://www.marxists.org/francais/broue/works/1961/00/PBET_Esp_1_11.htm | website = Guerra di Classe | date = 1936-11-05}}</ref>\n\nBerneri was also very critical of the [[Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional del Trabajo|CNT]]-[[Federaci\u00f3n Anarquista Ib\u00e9rica|FAI]]'s participation in the Republican government. Berneri worried about the growing isolation of the revolutionary and libertarian achievements in [[Revolutionary Catalonia|Catalonia]], [[Regional Defence Council of Aragon|Aragon]] and [[Sovereign Council of Asturias and Le\u00f3n|other regions]], and fought vigorously for the close connection of war and revolution. Such is the substance of many of his articles and speeches, such as of the famous open letter to the anarchist [[Ministry of Health (Spain)|Minister of Health]] [[Federica Montseny]], who with three other anarchists participated in the government of [[Largo Caballero]]: <ref>Camillo Berneri, ''[http://www.theyliewedie.org/ressources/biblio/fr/Berneri_Camillo_ -_Lettre_ouverte_a_la_camarade_Frederica_Montseny.html Lettre ouverte \u00e0 la camarade Frederica Montseny]''</ref>\n\n{{quote|The time has come to understand whether the anarchists in the government are [[vestals]] of the fire, which is about to go out, or whether they now serve only as the [[Phrygian cap]] of politicians, flirting with the enemy or with the forces of restoration of the \"republic of all classes.\" The dilemma of war or revolution no longer makes sense. The only significant dilemma is this: either victory over Franco through a revolutionary war, or defeat. <ref> Collectif, [http://kropot.free.fr/anarchie-histoire3.htm '' Barcelone, mai 1937 - la contre-r\u00e9volution '', in '' Les Anars des origines \u00e0 hier soir ''], Alternative libertaire, 1996 </ref>}}\n\nIn his 1936 book ''Thought and Battle'', Berneri gave critical comments on the situation, warning of the danger of a [[Stalinist]] coup, and marked his surprise at the \"anarchist government.\" His political suggestions for hitting the operational bases of fascism were numerous, though unheeded, such as [[Proclamation of Independence of Morocco|proclaiming the independence of Morocco]], coordinating military efforts and gradually strengthening socialization. \n\n=== Political assassination ===\n\nBerneri was soon exposing the fierce repressions carried out by Stalinists]] that had prevailed since the advent of the government of [[Juan Negr\u00edn]]: the victims of massacres and disappearances included thousands of non-communists, anarchists and also [[Anti-Stalinist left|non-Stalinist communists]], like the [[POUM]]. On May 5, 1937, Camillo Berneri and his anarchist friend [[Francesco Barbieri]] were taken out of their apartment by a dozen plainclothes men with red armbands and policemen. The corpses of the two Italian anarchists were found riddled with bullets. [[Giovanna Berneri]] raised the children of [[Antonio Cieri]], who also fell in Spain. On Camillo Berneri's death, the [[Italian Socialist Party|socialist]] leader [[Pietro Nenni]] wrote: \"If the anarchist Berneri had fallen on a barricade in Barcelona, \u200b\u200bfighting against the popular government, we would have nothing to say, and in the severity of his destiny we would find the strict law of the revolution. But Berneri was assassinated, and we must say it\".\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Anarchism in Italy]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite book |last1=D'Errico |first1=Stefano |title=Anarchismo e politica: nel problemismo e nella critica all'anarchismo del ventesimo secolo, il programma minimo dei libertari del terzo millennio : rilettura antologica e biografica di Camillo Berneri |date=2007 |language=Italian |isbn=978-88-8483-527-7 |publisher=Mimesis |location=Milano |oclc=849145792 |df=mdy-all }}\n* {{Cite encyclopedia |last1=De Felice |first1=Renzo |authorlink=Renzo De Felice |title=BERNERI, Camillo Luigi |volume=9 |date=1967 |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/camillo-luigi-berneri_(Dizionario-Biografico) |language=it-IT |encyclopedia=[[Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani]] |df=mdy-all }}\n* {{Cite book |last1=De Maria |first1=Carlo |title=Camillo Berneri: tra anarchismo e liberalismo |date=2004 |language=Italian |isbn=978-88-464-6041-7 |publisher=F. Angeli |location=Milano |oclc=57075335 |df=mdy-all }}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Guidi |first1=Flavio |title=Nostra patria mondo intero: Camillo Berneri e 'Guerra di classe' a Barcellona |date=2010 |language=Italian |isbn=978-88-910-0960-9 |publisher=Gruppo Editoriale l'Espresso |location=Roma |oclc=898188437 |df=mdy-all }}\n* {{cite book|last=Lane|first=A. T.|title=Biographical Dictionary of European Labor Leaders|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VlR8YCE8lkQC|year=1995|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-26456-6}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://struggle.ws/berneri.html Writings of Camillo Berneri]\n<!--*[http://anarchyisorder.org/onewebmedia/Berneri,%20Camillo%20-%20Selected%20Writings.pdf Selected Writings]-->\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120621024615/http://www.archivioberneri.it/ Berneri Archive] {{in lang|it}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berneri, Camillo}}\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lodi, Lombardy]]\n[[Category:Italian anarchists]]\n[[Category:Anarcho-communists]]\n[[Category:Italian journalists]]\n[[Category:Italian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Murdered anarchists]]\n[[Category:Murdered male writers]]\n[[Category:Italian people of the Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:Italian people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Spain]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Spain]]\n[[Category:University of Florence faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Italian military personnel of World War I]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=November 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox philosopher\n| name = Camillo Berneri\n| image = Camillo_Berneri.jpg\n| birth_name = Luigi Camillo Berneri \n| birth_date = May 20, 1897\n| birth_place = [[Lodi]], [[Lombardy]],<br>{{flag | Italy | 1861}}\n| death_date = May 5, 1937\n| death_place = [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]],<br>{{flag | Spain | 1931}}\n| alma_mater = [[University of Florence]]\n| school_tradition = [[20th-century philosophy]]\n| main_interests = [[Anarchism]], [[Antifascism]]\n}}\n'''Camillo Berneri''' (also known as '''Camillo da Lodi'''; May 28, 1897, [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]] \u2013 May 5, 1937, [[Barcelona]]) was an [[Italy|Italian]] professor of [[philosophy]], [[anarchist]] militant, propagandist and theorist. He was married to [[Giovanna Berneri]], and was father of [[Marie-Louise Berneri]] and [[Giliana Berneri]], all of whom were also anarchists.\n\n== Biography ==\n=== Early years ===\nCamillo Berneri was born in [[Lodi, Lombardy|Lodi]] on May 20, 1897. His father was a local [[Redshirts (Italy)|redshirt]] official from [[Province of Brescia|Brescia]], his mother was a a primary school teacher from [[Emilia (region of Italy)|Emilia]] and his grandfather was a [[Carbonari]] and a follower of [[Giuseppe Mazzini]].<ref name=\"Dictionary\">{{Cite journal|title= Berneri, Camillo Luigi|journal=Biographical Dictionary of European Labor Leaders|volume=1|first=A. Thomas|last=Lane|page=141-142|isbn=0-313-29899-8|year=1995|url=https://books.google.es/books/about/Biographical_Dictionary_of_European_Labo.html?id=VlR8YCE8lkQC&redir_esc=y}}</ref> His childhood was marked by physical suffering. In just a few months, he became [[malnourished]]. In 1904, Camillo fell ill with [[typhoid fever]], and later [[gastroenteritis]]. He moved with his family first to [[Milan]], then to [[Palermo]], to [[Forl\u00ec]], to [[Varallo Sesia]] and, finally, to [[Reggio Emilia]]. Here, in 1912, Berneri became a member of the ''Reggio Emilia Socialist Youth Federation''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://struggle.ws/spain/berneri.html|title=Camillo Berneri \u2013 Biography of the Italian anarchist|author=|website=struggle.ws|date=2011-05-25|publisher=}}</ref> He joined its Central Committee and collaborated with the federation's national organ. But after intense discussions, in particular with [[Torquato Gobbi]], a bookbinder and member of the ''International Committee of Anarchist Actions'', he left the federation in 1915. In an open letter, Bernery criticized the group for its [[red tape]] and \"lack of devotion.\"<ref name=\"Aktion\">Camillo Berneri, ''[https://www.anarchismus.at/anarchistische-klassiker/camillo-berneri/88-camillo-berneri-der-arbeiterkult Der Arbeiterkult]'', 1934 (''[[Die Aktion]]'', Nr. 170/174, July 1997)</ref><ref name=\"Mimmo\">{{cite book |first= Mimmo |last=Franzinelli|title= I tentacoli dell'Ovra. Agenti, collaboratori e vittime della polizia politica fascista |publisher= Bollati Boringhieri |year= 1999}}</ref> In 1916 he moved to [[Arezzo]] where he attended high school.\n\n{{quote|The socialist movement began its catastrophic descent into the foundations of destructive egoism, thereby following the trajectory of the moral strength of Christianity, which became powerful thanks to its martyrs and fell into decline when the sacrifices of its supporters ceased. [...] We need a new upsurge, we need a return to the time when to love the Idea meant not to be afraid of death and not to sacrifice our whole lives for the sake of complete submission. <ref>[[Frank Mintz]], [http://www.fondation-besnard.org/spip.php?article326 ''Camillo Berneri et Francesco Barbieri''].</ref>}}\n\nBerneri joined the [[Anarchism in Italy|Italian anarchist movement]]. He described his departure from [[socialism]] with the words: \u201cThe ideal worker of [[Marxism]] or socialism is a mythical figure. It stems from the metaphysics of socialist romanticism and is not historically proven.\u201d<ref name=\"Aktion\"/> He was struck by the gesture of his comrades, who, despite leaving, wanted him to chair their last meeting in Reggio, and the gesture of his mentor [[Camillo Prampolini]], who called him to find out the reasons for their disagreement. Berneri would always point to \u201cpleasant memories of the socialist period.\u201d<ref name=\"Psychology\">{{cite book|title='' Mussolini-Psychology of a dictator ''|first=Camillo|last=Berneri|publisher=Joint Action Editions|editor=[[Pier Carlo Masini]]|location=Milan|date=1966|page=115\u2014117}}</ref> In 1916, he moved to Arezzo, where he graduated from high school.\n\nOn January 4, 1917, he married in [[Giovanna Berneri|Giovanna Caleffi]], his mother's former pupil. Three months after the wedding, he was called up for military service, however, he was removed from service due to a serious illness. After three years of military service, he was forced to leave the [[Military Academy of Modena]] because of his [[anti-militarist]] activities. Under protection, he was sent to the front and twice brought before a [[military court]]. In 1919 he was confined to the island of [[Pianosa]] because of his participation in a [[Biennio Rosso|general strike on July 20-21, 1919]]. Dismissed from the army in 1919, he began to work diligently with the [[Umanit\u00e0 Nova|anarchist press]] and participated in the creation of the [[Union of Anarchist Communist of Italy|Union of Italian Anarchists]].<ref> '' Camillo Berneri (Lodi 1897-Barcelona 1937) '', Europe of tomorrow, biographical dictionary </ref> Being a convinced anti-militarist, he wrote: \u201cslaughter, robbery, rape, this is war! To satisfy his lust, the vile person takes on the courage that leaves him when he must save his neighbor from danger or start a dangerous and painful business. In a warmed-up and blood-soaked atmosphere of war, an ordinary person falls into barbarism, and sometimes even turns into a beast.\u201d<ref name=\"Aktion\"/> In 1920, he actively participated in the seizure of factories in [[Northern Italy]]. He also made friends with [[Errico Malatesta]] and [[Luigi Fabbri]]. \n\nAfter the war, he graduated from the [[University of Florence]], where Camillo was a student of [[Gaetano Salvemini]]. He then became a professor of philosophy at the university and later went on to teach philosophy at [[University of Camerino|Camerino]].\n\nWhen the [[Italian fascists|fascists]] seized power, Camillo refused to be loyal to the regime. Berneri's aversion to [[fascism]] was ready and decisive, he maintained contact with the [[Florentine]] [[anti-fascists]]. Berneri's activity in the Union of Italian Anarchists was very intense in those years. When the [[Fascist Italy (1922\u20131943)|fascist dictatorship]] intensified, in May 1926, Berneri was forced to flee the country to [[Third French Republic|France]]. His wife, [[Giovanna Berneri]],<ref> {{Cite web | url = http://www.ephemanar.net/mai04.html#caleffi | title = Giovannina Caleffi | author = | website = [[L'\u00c9ph\u00e9m\u00e9ride Anarchiste]] | date = | publisher =}} </ref> and his daughters [[Marie Louise Berneri]]<ref> {{Cite web | url = http://www.ephemanar.net/avril13.html#bernerimarie|title=Marie Louise Berneri | author = | website = [[L'\u00c9ph\u00e9m\u00e9ride Anarchiste]] | date = | publisher =}} </ref> and [[Giliana Berneri]]<ref> {{Cite web | url = http://www.ephemanar.net/octobre05.html#bernerigiliana | title = Giliana Berneri | author = | website = [[L'\u00c9ph\u00e9m\u00e9ride Anarchiste]] | date = | publisher =}} </ref> joined him soon after.<ref> {{Cite web | url = https://libcom.org/history/berneri-luigi-camillo-1897-1937 | title = Berneri, Luigi Camillo, 1897-1937 | author = | website = Libcom.org | date = 2004-09-21 | publisher =}} </ref>\n\n=== Emigration and police harassment ===\nBerneri was arrested in April 1927, after an international conference in [[L'Ha\u00ff-les-Roses]]. On December 11, 1928, he was expelled from France and until 1930 was constantly harassed by the [[Law enforcement in Belgium|Belgian]], [[Law enforcement in France|French]], [[Law enforcement in the Netherlands|Dutch]], [[Law enforcement in Germany|German]] and [[Grand Ducal Police|Luxembourg]] police during subsequent transfers and spent a lot of time in prison. He received a residence permit in France only in 1935, shortly before leaving for Spain. However, he continued to be widely published in the anarchist press in [[Fascist Italy|Italy]], [[Switzerland]], the [[USA]] and [[Third French Republic|France]]. <ref> {{Cite web | url = http://www.anarca-bolo.ch/cbach/biografie.php? Id = 4 | title = Berneri Camillo Luigi | author = | website = anarca-bolo.ch | date = | publisher =}} </ref>\n\nDespite all his limitations, this period allowed him to read books on various topics such as [[science]], [[psychology]] and [[teleology]]. He wrote [[anti-religious]] articles and brochures as well as pieces on the [[Women's rights|emancipation of women]]. He also completed his dissertation, ''The Anti-Semitic Jew'', where he studied the forced or voluntary [[Jewish assimilation|assimilation of Jews]]. The poet [[Andre Speer]], considered this book \u201cof paramount importance\u201d. Other important writings of his during this time were ''Spying'', ''Fascist Spying Abroad'' and ''Mussolini conquering the Balearic Islands''.\n\nHe also wrote about anarchism, where he defends personal positions:\n\n{{quote|We must move away from romanticism. Look at the masses, I would say, in perspective. There are not homogeneous people, but crowds, diverse, divided into groups. There is no revolutionary will of the masses, but revolutionary moments in which the masses are a huge lever.}}\n\n{{quote|If we want to achieve a significant revision of our revolutionary power, we must get rid of ideological [[a priori]]s and conveniently postponing the solution of tactical and constructive problems for tomorrow. I mean that the biggest danger of stopping and deviating from the revolution lies in the conservative tendency of the masses.}}\n\n=== Spanish Civil War ===\n[[File: Berneri1.jpg | alt = | thumb | Camillo Berneri in 1936]]\nOnce the [[Spanish Civil War]] broke out, Berneri was among the first to rush to [[Revolutionary Catalonia|Catalonia]], the center of a revolution spearheaded by the [[Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional del Trabajo]]: here he found himself alongside [[Carlo Rosselli]] with a large number of [[Anti-fascism#Italy: against Fascism and Mussolini|Italian]] and [[International Brigades|International]] anti-fascists.<ref> {{Cite web | url = https://gimenologues.org/spip.php?Article685 | title = Les Italiens - Charla sur les volontaires internationaux | author = | website = gimenologues.org | date = 2016-10-06 | publisher =}} </ref> Beyond militant solidarity, Carlo Rosselli was tied to his critical support for the prospects of [[Bolshevism]], while in those years Camillo Berneri collaborated with the clandestine organ of the libertarian socialist movement \"Giustizia e Libert\u00e0\", arguing with Rosselli on the stark differences between [[libertarian socialism]] and [[Authoritarian socialism|despotic socialism]]. Together with Rosselli, he organized the first column of Italian volunteers to fight on the [[Aragon front]], which were incorporated into the militia column of [[Joaqu\u00edn Ascaso]]. On August 28, 1936, Camillo Berneri took part in [[Battle of Monte Pelado]] near [[Huesca]]: \u201cWe defended our position with 130 people against 600, hardened and with strong weapons, for four hours of battle.\" He eventually needed to leave the front due to medical problems and returned to Barcelona, \u200b\u200bwhere he created and was editor-in-chief of the newspaper ''Class War'', also collaborating in the CNT-FAI radio station in Barcelona. During his stay in Barcelona, \u200b\u200bBerneri came to be under the surveillance of [[OVRA]], the secret police of fascist Italy.<ref>{{cite book|last=Graham| first=Helen|title=The Spanish Republic at War 1936-1939 | year = 2002 | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]]|page=295}}</ref>\n\nBerneri was a staunch defender of the [[Spanish Revolution]] and was one of the first to argue that only an [[anti-capitalist]] struggle can counter [[fascism]] and that the problem with [[anti-fascism]] is the rejection of the principles of the [[Social revolution]]. He constantly reiterates that revolution must be won on social, not military, grounds. Thus, he opposed the [[Militarism | militarization]] of the militias, which had brought the first victories against state forces. <ref> {{cite book| title = Guerre de Classes en Espagne et textes libertaires|publisher = [[Spartacus Editions]] | date = 1977}}</ref> He stood against those who advocated the idea of \u200b\u200b\u201cfirst beat [[Francisco Franco|Franco]]\u201d, and stood for the close connection between the war and the social revolution: \u201cVictory in war is necessary; however, the war will not be won by limiting the problem to the purely military conditions of victory, but by linking them to the political and social conditions of victory. '' '<ref>{{Cite news|title = La R\u00e9volution et la Guerre d\u2019Espagne | last=Brou\u00e9|first=P.| url = https://www.marxists.org/francais/broue/works/1961/00/PBET_Esp_1_11.htm | website = Guerra di Classe | date = 1936-11-05}}</ref>\n\nBerneri was also very critical of the [[Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional del Trabajo|CNT]]-[[Federaci\u00f3n Anarquista Ib\u00e9rica|FAI]]'s participation in the Republican government. Berneri worried about the growing isolation of the revolutionary and libertarian achievements in [[Revolutionary Catalonia|Catalonia]], [[Regional Defence Council of Aragon|Aragon]] and [[Sovereign Council of Asturias and Le\u00f3n|other regions]], and fought vigorously for the close connection of war and revolution. Such is the substance of many of his articles and speeches, such as of the famous open letter to the anarchist [[Ministry of Health (Spain)|Minister of Health]] [[Federica Montseny]], who with three other anarchists participated in the government of [[Largo Caballero]]: <ref>Camillo Berneri, ''[http://www.theyliewedie.org/ressources/biblio/fr/Berneri_Camillo_ -_Lettre_ouverte_a_la_camarade_Frederica_Montseny.html Lettre ouverte \u00e0 la camarade Frederica Montseny]''</ref>\n\n{{quote|The time has come to understand whether the anarchists in the government are [[vestals]] of the fire, which is about to go out, or whether they now serve only as the [[Phrygian cap]] of politicians, flirting with the enemy or with the forces of restoration of the \"republic of all classes.\" The dilemma of war or revolution no longer makes sense. The only significant dilemma is this: either victory over Franco through a revolutionary war, or defeat. <ref> Collectif, [http://kropot.free.fr/anarchie-histoire3.htm '' Barcelone, mai 1937 - la contre-r\u00e9volution '', in '' Les Anars des origines \u00e0 hier soir ''], Alternative libertaire, 1996 </ref>}}\n\nIn his 1936 book ''Thought and Battle'', Berneri gave critical comments on the situation, warning of the danger of a [[Stalinist]] coup, and marked his surprise at the \"anarchist government.\" His political suggestions for hitting the operational bases of fascism were numerous, though unheeded, such as [[Proclamation of Independence of Morocco|proclaiming the independence of Morocco]], coordinating military efforts and gradually strengthening socialization. \n\n=== Political assassination ===\n\nBerneri was soon exposing the fierce repressions carried out by Stalinists]] that had prevailed since the advent of the government of [[Juan Negr\u00edn]]: the victims of massacres and disappearances included thousands of non-communists, anarchists and also [[Anti-Stalinist left|non-Stalinist communists]], like the [[POUM]]. On May 5, 1937, Camillo Berneri and his anarchist friend [[Francesco Barbieri]] were taken out of their apartment by a dozen plainclothes men with red armbands and policemen. The corpses of the two Italian anarchists were found riddled with bullets. [[Giovanna Berneri]] raised the children of [[Antonio Cieri]], who also fell in Spain. On Camillo Berneri's death, the [[Italian Socialist Party|socialist]] leader [[Pietro Nenni]] wrote: \"If the anarchist Berneri had fallen on a barricade in Barcelona, \u200b\u200bfighting against the popular government, we would have nothing to say, and in the severity of his destiny we would find the strict law of the revolution. But Berneri was assassinated, and we must say it\".\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Anarchism in Italy]]\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite book |last1=D'Errico |first1=Stefano |title=Anarchismo e politica: nel problemismo e nella critica all'anarchismo del ventesimo secolo, il programma minimo dei libertari del terzo millennio : rilettura antologica e biografica di Camillo Berneri |date=2007 |language=Italian |isbn=978-88-8483-527-7 |publisher=Mimesis |location=Milano |oclc=849145792 |df=mdy-all }}\n* {{Cite encyclopedia |last1=De Felice |first1=Renzo |authorlink=Renzo De Felice |title=BERNERI, Camillo Luigi |volume=9 |date=1967 |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/camillo-luigi-berneri_(Dizionario-Biografico) |language=it-IT |encyclopedia=[[Dizionario Biografico degli Italiani]] |df=mdy-all }}\n* {{Cite book |last1=De Maria |first1=Carlo |title=Camillo Berneri: tra anarchismo e liberalismo |date=2004 |language=Italian |isbn=978-88-464-6041-7 |publisher=F. Angeli |location=Milano |oclc=57075335 |df=mdy-all }}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Guidi |first1=Flavio |title=Nostra patria mondo intero: Camillo Berneri e 'Guerra di classe' a Barcellona |date=2010 |language=Italian |isbn=978-88-910-0960-9 |publisher=Gruppo Editoriale l'Espresso |location=Roma |oclc=898188437 |df=mdy-all }}\n* {{cite book|last=Lane|first=A. T.|title=Biographical Dictionary of European Labor Leaders|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VlR8YCE8lkQC|year=1995|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-26456-6}}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://struggle.ws/berneri.html Writings of Camillo Berneri]\n<!--*[http://anarchyisorder.org/onewebmedia/Berneri,%20Camillo%20-%20Selected%20Writings.pdf Selected Writings]-->\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120621024615/http://www.archivioberneri.it/ Berneri Archive] {{in lang|it}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berneri, Camillo}}\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1937 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Lodi, Lombardy]]\n[[Category:Italian anarchists]]\n[[Category:Anarcho-communists]]\n[[Category:Italian journalists]]\n[[Category:Italian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Murdered anarchists]]\n[[Category:Murdered male writers]]\n[[Category:Italian people of the Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:Italian people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Spain]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Spain]]\n[[Category:University of Florence faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Italian military personnel of World War I]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Lodi\u2192Lodi, Lombardy,Florentine\u2192Florence,Fascist Italy\u2192Fascist Italy (1922\u20131943),Spanish Revolution\u2192Spanish Revolution of 1936", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camillo_Berneri"}
