rect=no"}
{"title_page": "Paul Hendy", "text_new": "{{short description|Script-writer, novelist, director, producer and filmmaker}}\n'''Paul Hendy''' (born 22 July 1966) is a script-writer, novelist, director, producer and filmmaker.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.jandpr.com/hollywood-award-for-local-star/|title=Hollywood Award for Local Star.|work=J&PR Ltd|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2baabce4dd|title=Paul Hendy|work=BFI|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.penguin.com.au/authors/paul-hendy|title=Paul Hendy|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukgameshows.com/ukgs/Paul_Hendy|title=Paul Hendy \u2013 UKGameshows|website=www.ukgameshows.com|access-date=2018-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/whats-on/out-and-about/paul-hendy-twelve-years-at-the-helm-of-sheffield-s-christmas-panto-we-aspire-to-a-west-end-standard-1-9482940|title=Paul Hendy: Twelve years at the helm of Sheffield's Christmas panto \u2013 'We aspire to a West End standard'|website=www.thestar.co.uk|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2baabce4dd|title=Paul Hendy|website=BFI|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref>.  In his early career (1990\u20132006), he was a TV presenter hosting the [[British Academy of Film and Television Arts|BAFTA]] nominated ''Dear Mr Barker'' ([[BBC]])<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/d1a0f7695c284307b3dd20751a2ff29d|title=Dear Mr Barker \u2013 BBC One London \u2013 30 October 1998 \u2013 BBC Genome|issue=3898|pages=118|journal=The Radio Times|access-date=2018-06-18|date=1998-10-22}}</ref>, ''[[Don't Try This at Home (TV series)|Don\u2019t Try This at Home]]'' ([[ITV (TV network)|ITV]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukgameshows.com/ukgs/Don't_Try_This_at_Home!|title=Don't Try This at Home! \u2013 UKGameshows|website=www.ukgameshows.com|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>, ''[[The Disney Club]]'' (ITV)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b7bcdc9b2|title=Disney Club Special (1992)|work=BFI|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>, and ''[[Wheel of Fortune (UK game show)|Wheel of Fortune]]'' (ITV)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sharetv.com/shows/wheel_of_fortune_uk/cast/ho_st|title=Host \u2013 Paul Hendy \u2013 Wheel of Fortune (UK) Characters \u2013 ShareTV|website=sharetv.com|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>.  He was a regular reporter on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\u2019s ''[[This Morning (TV programme)|This Morning]]'' and hosted \u2018''Stash the Cash\u2019''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukgameshows.com/ukgs/Stash|title=Stash \u2013 UKGameshows|website=www.ukgameshows.com|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>. \n\nIn 2017 Hendy wrote, produced and directed a short film The Last Laugh which sees three legendary British comedians in a dressing room discussing the secret of comedy and what it means to be funny. In 2018 Hendy produced and directed Mr Sunshine (written by [[Tim Whitnall]]), a short film on the life of Eric Morecambe<ref name=\":2\" />.   \n\nIn 2004, Hendy wrote the novel ''Diary of a C-List Celeb''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The diary of a C-list celeb|last=Paul.|first=Hendy|date=2004|publisher=Bantam|isbn=978-0553816259|location=London|oclc=59262296|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/diaryofclistcele00paul}}</ref>, a fictionalised account of his experiences in television and the entertainment industry.  The novel was published by Bantam ([[Penguin Random House]]). In 2005, the screen rights for ''Diary of a C-List Celeb'' were optioned by [[Hartswood Films]]. In 2006, Hendy wrote the sequel, ''Who Killed Simon Peters?''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Who killed Simon Peters?|last=1966\u2013|first=Hendy, Paul|date=2009|publisher=Bantam Books|isbn=9780553816266|location=London|oclc=276224247}}</ref> also published by Bantam (Penguin Random House).\n\n== Early career ==\nHendy's career started as a member of The [[National Youth Theatre]] of Great Britain, playing the part of Billy Casper in Kes in 1980.  His first break into television came in 1990 when he hosted eighty episodes of BSB's [[Raise the Roof (game show)|''Raise the Roof'']].  Hendy was then chosen to present ITV's Sunday morning flagship show ''[[The Disney Club]]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b7d50c2b7|title=Disney Club[23/01/94] (1994)|website=BFI|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref>. After leaving ''The Disney Club'', Hendy went to the [[BBC]] and hosted the Saturday morning show [[Parallels (TV series)|''Parallel 9'']] which was broadcast live from [[Pinewood Studios]]. He has also presented ''Disney Summer Holidays'' (ITV), ''For Amusement Only'' (BBC), ''Highly Sprung'' (BBC), ''Travel Bug'' (an Action Time Production for BBC) and three series of the BAFTA nominated ''Dear Mr Barker'' (BBC)<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0376941/|title=Paul Hendy|website=IMDb|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>. \n\nHe was host of ITV1's game show [[Wheel of Fortune (UK game show)|''Wheel of Fortune'']] (2001) with [[Terri Seymour]]<ref>{{Citation|last=Pluginthetv|title=Wheel of Fortune UK Opening Titles 2001|date=2009-03-25|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ge3mcdg1g5g|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref> and ITV1's prime time Saturday night show [[Don't Try This at Home (TV series)|''Don't Try This at Home'']] with [[Davina McCall]], which ran for four series (1998\u20132001)\n\nHendy was a regular reporter for ITV's [[This Morning (TV programme)|''This Morning'']] and a guest presenter on [[GMTV (TV programme)|GMTV]]. He hosted ''Talking TV'' (BBC1), ''Walk Over History'' (Meridian) and ''The Dog Listener'' (Ch5). He has also hosted ''Kicked Into Touch'' (Meridian) and ''Stash'' (ITV). He also hosted a cinema review show called ''The Box Office Boys'' (BFBS)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/57387943|title=Box Office Boys \u2013 Movie Review Show|website=Vimeo|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref>, and featured on an episode of ''Surprising Stars''<ref>{{Citation|last=Karl Jenkinson|title=From \"Loose Women\", Kate Thornton in Hidden Camera Show|date=2010-07-17|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gU2_szk7f0k|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref> with Kate Thornton.\n\nFrom 1994\u20132000, Hendy hosted the international music event The Global Rock Challenge, and in 1999 he was asked to host the Grand Final in Melbourne, Australia.\n\nFrom 1987-89, his best friend and fellow theatre actor was Shaun Johnson.  Hendy and Johnson used to practice stunts together.  When Paul\u2019s career took off, Shaun remained his most loyal fan.\n\nIn the early 1980s, Hendy worked at Butlins. He invited Johnson to help put on entertainment under Hendy\u2019s direction. The next year, Hendy went to America to work at Disney. In support, Johnson changed his middle name to Paul by deed poll. \n\nBetween 1989-91 Paul Hendy was executive joke writer for McVities Penguin biscuits. In a sit down interview with Fred Dineage, Hendy explained why he left the job after two years - \"I wanted to spread my wings. Jokes about penguins were just the tip of the iceberg, if you snow what I mean?\"\n\n== Film ==\nIn 2016, Hendy wrote, directed and produced the short film, ''The Last Laugh''. The film won Best UK Film and Best UK Short at the Manchester Film Festival as well as many other International film awards including Best Comedy Drama at [[LA Film Festival|Los Angeles Independent Film Festival]] and Best Supporting Actor at Sydney Independent Film Festival.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 2018, Hendy and his production company Evolution, optioned the film rights to [[Tim Whitnall]]\u2019s [[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier]] play,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://officiallondontheatre.com/olivier-awards/winners/olivier-winners-2010/|title=Olivier Awards Winners 2010 -Official London Theatre|website=Olivier Awards|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref> [[Morecambe (play)|''Morecambe'']]. The adaptation, currently entitled Mr Sunshine after the short teaser film, is set to begin principal photography in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/whats-on/news/film-project-for-panto-producer-190775/|title=Film project for panto producer|date=2018-09-15|website=Kent Online|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Productions|first=Evolution|title=MR SUNSHINE (teaser)|date=2018-06-15|url=https://vimeo.com/275322351|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/film/mr_sunshine/|title=Mr Sunshine \u2013 Film|last=Guide|first=British Comedy|website=British Comedy Guide|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/film/news/3207/eric_morecambe_film_biopic_bob_golding/|title=Eric Morecambe's life story to be turned into feature film|last=Guide|first=British Comedy|date=2018-07-30|website=British Comedy Guide|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/film/news/3207/eric_morecambe_film_biopic_bob_golding/|title=Eric Morecambe's life story to be turned into feature film|last=Guide|first=British Comedy|date=2018-07-30|website=British Comedy Guide|access-date=2019-03-13}}</ref>\n\n== Novels ==\nIn 2004, Hendy wrote the novel ''Diary of a C-List Celeb''<ref name=\":0\" />, a fictionalised account of his experiences in television and the entertainment industry. The novel was published by Bantam (Penguin Random House).\n\n[[Davina McCall]] called the book \u2018Bloody genius, very funny and leg-crossingly embarrassing!\u2019 and [[Declan Donnelly]] ([[Ant & Dec|Ant and Dec]]) called it \u2018Very funny\u2026 and spookily close to the truth\u2019.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/diaryofclistcele00paul|title=The Diary Of A C-List Celeb|last=results|first=search|date=2010-09-30|publisher=Transworld Digital|isbn=9780553816259|location=London|language=English|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Hendy wrote the sequel, ''Who Killed Simon Peters?'' also published by Bantam (Penguin Random House).<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n== Radio ==\nOn radio, Hendy has hosted his own late night phone-in show, three times a week on [[LBC]] (1996). He has also presented a series of one-off specials for [[British Forces Broadcasting Service|BFBS]] in which he interviewed celebrities about their all time favourite top ten records (2001).{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\n== Evolution Productions ==\n[[File:Evolution Logo.svg|thumb|Evolution Productions]]\nIn 2005, Hendy set up Evolution Productions with his wife, Emily Wood. They produce films, large-scale theatrical productions and national theatre tours in the UK and abroad<ref>{{Cite book|title=Actors & performers yearbook 2018 : essential contacts for stage, screen and radio|others=Trott, Lloyd (Dramaturg)|isbn=9781350030220|edition=Fourteenth|location=London|oclc=1008757389}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017/18, their production of [[Peter Pan]] at [[Marlowe Theatre|The Marlowe Theatre]] in Canterbury was seen by over a record breaking 100,000 people<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://marlowetheatre.com/we-have-had-over-100000-people-come-and-see-peter-pan-thats-a-record-breaker-%F0%9F%98%80-massive-thank-you-to-all-of-you/we-have-had-over-100000-people-come-and-see-peter-pan-thats-a-record-breaker-%F0%9F%98%80-massive-thank-you-to-all-of-you-2/|title=We have had over 100,000 people come and see Peter Pan, that's a record breaker ???? massive thank you to all of you. \u2013 The Marlowe|work=The Marlowe|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>. The British Theatre Guide called the show \u2018one of the best productions in the country\u2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/peter-pan-15332|title=Theatre review: Peter Pan at Marlowe Theatre, Canterbury|website=www.britishtheatreguide.info|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>\n\nEvolution Productions currently produce 8 pantomimes each year around the country, and have performed with some notable performers including: [[Stephen Mulhern]], [[Mister Maker|Phil Gallagher]], [[Rita Simons]], [[Scott Maslen]], [[Gareth Gates]] and even [[George Takei]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/canterbury/news/popular-tv-host-named-as-92923/|title=Popular TV host named as new panto star for Canterbury show|work=Kent Online|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://the-void.co.uk/theatre/review-snow-white-and-the-seven-dwarfs-marlowe-theatre-canterbury-760/|title=Review: Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs \u2013 Marlowe Theatre Canterbury|last=Void|first=The|date=2015-12-11|work=The Void Magazine|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/uk-regional/article/Scott-Maslen-to-Lead-Marlowe-Theatres-ALADDIN-20140321|title=Scott Maslen to Lead Marlowe Theatre's ALADDIN|last=Desk|first=BWW News|work=BroadwayWorld.com|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent/news/gareth-gates-for-marlowe-panto-a65312/|title=Marlowe panto Gareth Gates|work=Kent Online|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/medway/news/aladdin-at-chathams-central-the-a90213/|title=Aladdin at Chatham's Central T|work=Kent Online|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>. Producing new and original pantomimes each year, complete with new sets and costumes.\n\n=== Awards ===\n\n==== Film awards ====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Award\n!Awarding Body\n!Result\n|-\n! rowspan=\"5\" |2017\n|Best UK Film\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Manchester Film Festival<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.maniff.com/maniff2017/|title=MANIFF 2017|website=Manchester Film Festival|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>\n|Won\n|-\n|Best UK Short\n|Won\n|-\n|Best Actor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |St Albans Film Festival<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stalbansfilmfestival.com/|title=St Albans Film Festival|website=www.stalbansfilmfestival.com|access-date=2018-06-18}}</ref>\n|Won\n|-\n|Best Film\n|Won\n|-\n|Best Short (Comedy)\n|International Film Festival of Word Cinema\n|Won\n|