s virginianus'')\n | Reptile = {{Plainlist|\n*[[American alligator]]\n*(''Alligator mississippiensis'')\n }}\n | Tree = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Magnolia grandiflora|Southern magnolia]]\n*(''Magnolia grandiflora'')\n }}\n | Beverage = Milk\n | Colors = red and blue\n | Dance = [[Clogging]]\n | Dinosaur =\n | Food = [[Sweet potato]]\n | Fossil =\n | Gemstone = Emerald\n | Mineral = Gold\n | Musical Instrument =\n | Poem =\n | Rock = Granite\n | Shell = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Eastern oyster]]\n*(Crassostrea virginica)\n }}\n | Ships =\n | Slogan = ''First Flight'' (unofficial)\n | Soil =\n | Sport =\n | Tartan =\n | Toy =\n | Other =\n | Route Marker = Ellipse sign 15.svg\n | Quarter = 2002 MS Proof.png\n | QuarterReleaseDate = 2002\n}}\n\n'''Mississippi''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=en-us-Mississippi.ogg|\u02cc|m|\u026a|s|\u1d7b|\u02c8|s|\u026a|p|i}}) is a [[U.S. state|state]] located in the [[Deep South]] region of the [[United States]]. Mississippi is the [[List of U.S. states and territories by area|32nd largest]] and [[List of U.S. states by population|34th-most populous]] of the [[List of states and territories of the United States|50 United States]]. Mississippi is bordered to the north by [[Tennessee]], to the east by [[Alabama]], to the south by the [[Gulf of Mexico]], to the southwest by [[Louisiana]], and to the northwest by [[Arkansas]]. Mississippi's western boundary is largely defined by the [[Mississippi River]]. [[Jackson, Mississippi|Jackson]] is both the state's [[List of capitals in the United States|capital]] and largest city. [[Jackson metropolitan area, Mississippi|Greater Jackson]], with an estimated population of 580,166 in 2018, is the most populous [[Metropolitan statistical area|metropolitan area]] in Mississippi and the [[List of metropolitan statistical areas|95th-most populous]] in the United States.\n\nOn December 10, 1817, Mississippi became the [[List of U.S. states by date of admission to the Union|20th state]] admitted to the Union. By 1860, Mississippi was the nation's top [[cotton]] producing state and [[Slavery in the United States|enslaved persons]] accounted for 55% of the state population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us/articles/161/cotton-in-a-global-economy-mississippi-1800-1860|title=Cotton in a Global Economy: Mississippi (1800-1860) {{!}} Mississippi History Now|website=mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref> Mississippi declared its [[Secession in the United States|secession]] from the Union on March 23, 1861, and was one of the seven original [[Confederate States of America|Confederate States]]. Following the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], it was restored to the Union on February 23, 1870.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The A to Z of the Civil War and Reconstruction|last=Richter, William L. (William Lee), 1942-|date=2009|publisher=Scarecrow Press|others=Richter, William L. (William Lee), 1942-|isbn=9780810863361|location=Lanham|oclc=435767707}}</ref>\n\nUntil the [[Great Migration (African American)|Great Migration]] of the 1930s, [[African Americans]] were a majority of Mississippi's population. Mississippi was the site of many prominent events during the [[Civil rights movement|American Civil Rights movement]], including the [[Ole Miss riot of 1962|1962 Ole Miss riots]], the 1963 assassination of [[Medgar Evers]], and the 1964 [[Murders of Chaney, Goodman, and Schwerner|Freedom Summer murders]]. Mississippi frequently ranks low among states in measures of health, education, and development, and high in measures of poverty.<ref name=\"America's Health Rankings\">{{cite web|url=http://www.americashealthrankings.org/MS|title=Mississippi Annual State Health Rankings\u20142013|website=America's Health Rankings|accessdate=October 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statemaster.com/graph/edu_per_of_peo_who_hav_com_hig_sch_inc_equ-completed-high-school-including-equivalency|title=Percent of People Who Have Completed High School (Including Equivalency) statistics\u2014states compared\u2014Statemaster|publisher=|accessdate=October 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://proximityone.com/stmhi0910.htm|title=State Median Household Income Patterns: 1990\u20132010|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=August 6, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globaldatalab.org/shdi/shdi/|title=Sub-national HDI\u2014Subnational HDI\u2014Global Data Lab|website=globaldatalab.org|access-date=2019-05-24}}</ref> In 2010, 37.3% of Mississippi's population was African American, the [[List of U.S. states and territories by African-American population|highest percentage for any state]].\n\nMississippi is almost entirely within the [[Gulf Coastal Plain|Gulf coastal plain]], and generally consists of [[Plain|lowland plains]] and low hills. The northwest remainder of the state consists of the [[Mississippi Delta]], a section of the [[Mississippi Alluvial Plain]]. Mississippi's highest point is [[Woodall Mountain]] at 807 feet (246 m) above sea level adjacent to the [[Cumberland Plateau]]; the lowest is the Gulf of Mexico. Mississippi has a [[humid subtropical climate]] classification.\n\n==Etymology==\n\nThe state's name is derived from the [[Mississippi River]], which flows along its western boundary. Settlers named it after the [[Ojibwe language|Ojibwe]] word ''misi-ziibi'' (\"Great River\").\n\n==Geography==\n\n[[File:Map of Mississippi NA.png|thumb|upright=1.35| ]]\n[[File:Wolf-River-swamp-North-Mississippi.jpg|thumb|Bottomland hardwood swamp near [[Ashland, Mississippi|Ashland]]]]\n\nMississippi is bordered to the north by [[Tennessee]], to the east by [[Alabama]], to the south by [[Louisiana]] and a narrow coast on the [[Gulf of Mexico]]; and to the west, across the Mississippi River, by Louisiana and [[Arkansas]].\n\nIn addition to its namesake, major rivers in Mississippi include the [[Big Black River (Mississippi)|Big Black River]], the [[Pearl River (Mississippi-Louisiana)|Pearl River]], the [[Yazoo River]], the [[Pascagoula River]], and the [[Tombigbee River]]. Major lakes include [[Ross Barnett Reservoir]], [[Arkabutla Lake]], [[Sardis Lake (Mississippi)|Sardis Lake]], and [[Grenada Lake]] with the largest lake being Sardis Lake.\n\nMississippi is entirely composed of [[lowland]]s, the highest point being [[Woodall Mountain]], in the [[foothills]] of the [[Cumberland Mountains]], {{convert|807|ft|m}} above [[sea level]]. The lowest point is sea level at the [[Gulf Coast]]. The state's mean elevation is {{convert|300|ft|m}} above sea level.\n\nMost of Mississippi is part of the East Gulf Coastal Plain. The [[coastal plain]] is generally composed of low hills, such as the Pine Hills in the south and the North Central Hills. The Pontotoc Ridge and the Fall Line Hills in the northeast have somewhat higher elevations. Yellow-brown [[loess]] soil is found in the western parts of the state. The northeast is a region of fertile black earth that extends into the [[Black Belt (region of Alabama)|Alabama Black Belt]].\n\nThe coastline includes large bays at [[Bay St. Louis, Mississippi|Bay St. Louis]], [[Biloxi, Mississippi|Biloxi]], and [[Pascagoula, Mississippi|Pascagoula]]. It is separated from the Gulf of Mexico proper by the shallow [[Mississippi Sound]], which is partially sheltered by [[Petit Bois Island (Mississippi)|Petit Bois Island]], [[Horn Island (Mississippi)|Horn Island]], [[Ship Island (Mississippi)|East and West Ship Islands]], [[Deer Island (Mississippi)|Deer Island]], [[Round Island (Mississippi)|Round Island]], and [[Cat Island (Mississippi)|Cat Island]].\n\nThe northwest remainder of the state consists of the [[Mississippi Delta]], a section of the [[Mississippi Alluvial Plain]]. The plain is narrow in the south and widens north of [[Vicksburg, Mississippi|Vicksburg]]. The region has rich soil, partly made up of [[silt]] which had been regularly deposited by the [[Flood plain|flood waters]] of the Mississippi River.\n\nAreas under the management of the [[National Park Service]] include:<ref>{{cite web|title=Mississippi |publisher=National Park Service |accessdate=July 16, 2008 |url=http://www.nps.gov/state/ms}}</ref>\n*[[Brices Cross Roads National Battlefield Site]] near [[Baldwyn, Mississippi|Baldwyn]]\n*[[Gulf Islands National Seashore]]\n*[[Natchez National Historical Park]] in [[Natchez, Mississippi|Natchez]]\n*[[Natchez Trace National Scenic Trail]] in [[Tupelo, Mississippi|Tupelo]]\n*[[Natchez Trace Parkway]]\n*[[Tupelo National Battlefield]] in Tupelo\n*[[Vicksburg National Military Park|Vicksburg National Military Park and Cemetery]] in [[Vicksburg, Mississippi|Vicksburg]]\n\n===Major cities and towns===\n\n[[File:JacksonMS Downtown Panorama.jpg|thumb|[[Jackson, Mississippi]]]]\n[[File:25thAve&13thSt.jpg|thumb|Northwest view of Gulfport Harbor Square Commercial Historic District]]\n[[File:Strawberry Patch Park 2009.jpg|thumb|Strawberry Patch Park, Madison]]\n[[File:Mississippi 90.jpg|thumb|Map with all counties and their county seats|alt=]]\n\nMississippi City Population Rankings of at least 50,000 ([[United States Census Bureau]] as of 2017):<ref name=\"Annual Population Estimates\">{{cite web|url=https://census.gov/data/tables/2017/demo/popest/total-cities-and-towns.html|title=Archived copy|accessdate=March 2, 2019}}. Retrieved September 20, 2013.</ref>\n{{columns-list|\n#[[Jackson, Mississippi|Jackson]] (166,965)\n#[[Gulfport, Mississippi|Gulfport]] (71,822)\n#[[Southaven, Mississippi|Southaven]] (54,031)\n}}\nMississippi City Population Rankings of at least 20,000 but fewer than 50,000 ([[United States Census Bureau]] as of 2017):<ref name=\"Annual Population Estimates\"/>\n{{columns-list|colwidth=20em|\n{{ordered list|start=4\n | [[Hattiesburg, Mississippi|Hattiesburg]] (46,377)\n | [[Biloxi, Mississippi|Biloxi]] (45,908)\n | [[Tupelo, Mississippi|Tupelo]] (38,114)\n | [[Meridian, Mississippi|Meridian]] (37,940)\n | [[Olive Branch, Mississippi|Olive Branch]] (37,435)\n | [[Greenville, Mississippi|Greenville]] (30,686)\n | [[Horn La